<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/space/1187024">www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/space/1187024</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Dec. 26, 2001, 8:07AM<br>
<br>
By ERIC BERGER <br>
Copyright 2001 Houston Chronicle Science Writer <br>
<br>
Beyond the considerable engineering and technical challenges of sending the first man to Mars lies another concern: <br>
<br>
What happens if an astronaut breaks a leg along the way? <br>
<br>
For nearly five years, a growing Houston-based consortium of scientists has attacked the questions surrounding the health effects of lengthy space travel on humans. <br>
<br>
NASA has steadily stepped up its support for the center, known as the National Space Biomedical Research Institute, which is housed at the Baylor College of Medicine. Its research budget this year topped $21 million. <br>
<br>
&quot;We just don't know whether people will be able to go to Mars and come back alive,&quot; said the center's newly named director, Dr. Jeffrey P. Sutton. &quot;Space travel is risky business.&quot; <br>
<br>
Astronauts exposed to long-term space travel face numerous risks, from trying to treat injuries in a low-gravity environment to bone and muscle loss and the psychological effects of being cooped up in a small area with the same people for years. Even on the international space station, where astronauts spend months in cramped isolation, there is not the psychological barrier of being in deep space months or years away from Earth. <br>
<br>
The space institute spends between $700,000 and $1.9 million a year funding each of about seven dozen projects at 71 institutions around the country. Consortium members include Baylor, Rice University, Texas A&amp;M University, Harvard Medical School and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. <br>
<br>
Some of the space institute's research, such as the beneficial effect of day and night light cycles on human sleep and performance, has already been implemented by space station crew members. <br>
<br>
Sutton says if the United States or an international group pursues a long-term space travel mission to Mars or another destination, the public will have to decide how much risk it is willing to accept. <br>
<br>
Given the expense of building large rockets and preparing for every contingency, there will be limits on what effects can be anticipated. There's still a low risk tolerance 15 years after the Challenger explosion, he said. <br>
<br>
Yet there is hope scientists have a fair grasp on the challenges astronauts would face. Humans have been in space for 40 years, after all, he said. <br>
<br>
One of the greatest, least understood concerns comes from long-term exposure of astronauts to deep-space radiation. Belts of this radiation in the solar system, as well as surges in the solar wind, can expose humans aboard rockets to doses hundreds of times greater than on Earth. <br>
<br>
Scientists are also concerned that, aside from possibly leading to cancer, such radiation would weaken immune systems. <br>
<br>
That's one area being studied by Dr. William Shearer, who is leading the institute's immunology and infection research team. <br>
<br>
In addition to possible radiation effects, close exposure to others over a long period could weaken the body's ability to fight disease. Shearer is studying this effect in Antarctic scientists, who are cooped up in small spaces during the long South Pole winter. <br>
<br>
The body's immune system holds any number of viruses in check at all times. If it weakens, the viruses could roam free. <br>
<br>
&quot;It's possible that in space the immune system might become weakened to the point that you could have very serious reactivated viruses,&quot; Shearer said. &quot;The more we look at these problems, the less hypothetical they become.&quot; <br>
<br>
Shearer views his team's challenge as one of proving that a weakened immune system is a real concern for astronauts. If that's the case, then several treatments are possible, he said. <br>
<br>
Drug therapies exist today that help children born without disease-fighting antibodies. Another option, if radiation weakens the immune system, is storing in a shielded area of the spacecraft the astronauts' bone-marrow stem cells, which, if injected, could restore the immune system. <br>
<br>
Another major problem facing astronauts is the muscle and bone loss that comes with living in a zero-gravity environment. <br>
<br>
In the movie 2001: A Space Odyssey, the astronauts exercise in a white room on a track. <br>
<br>
&quot;That's great,&quot; said Dr. Jay Shapiro, the institute's bone loss team leader. &quot;The only thing that Hollywood has assumed is that there is gravity.&quot; <br>
<br>
For the foreseeable future, producing artificial gravity, possibly by spinning a spacecraft to create a centrifugal effect on the outer wall of the vessel as depicted in 2001, remains an expensive and daunting engineering project. <br>
<br>
If there's no gravity, or very little, humans begin losing muscle from inactivity in as little as 11 days, and bone loss soon follows as no muscles pull upon them. Astronauts can lose 1 percent to 2 percent of their muscle and bone mass per month. <br>
<br>
Shapiro believes spinal-cord patients, typically healthy people who don't use their muscles for about four months, are good subjects to test the benefits of bone-loss drugs similar to those used by osteoporosis patients. Early trials have been successful, he said, and the next step is likely testing the medicine in a spaceflight setting. <br>
<br>
As the space institute's new director, Sutton has been on the job only a month. He plans to move to Houston from Boston next summer. <br>
<br>
Some of his colleagues, he said, have asked him why he would leave esteemed positions in the Northeast for, of all places, Houston. Sutton, 43, is head of the neural systems group at the Massachusetts General Hospital and is an associate professor at Harvard and MIT. <br>
<br>
His answer is simple: He sees space biomedicine as something on the order of developing a Star Trek-like medical tricorder for astronauts to take on long-duration trips. <br>
<br>
&quot;This is cutting-edge science,&quot; he said. &quot;And sending humans safely into outer space is a noble mission.&quot; <br>
