Remember the carnival ride Graviton?  The one everybody pukes on then it travels around hitting all the riders (ah, the good 'ol days)?  That doesn't cost much to make and isn't humungous in size.  Put that within a capsule and you can still have strong, stationary connections from the business end to the personel capsules.  The outer wall doesn't need to move, just the inside wall.  An AC or DC motor could be used to spin the wall, getting power from the nuke generator.  You could then stand &quot;upright&quot; headlong into the room and get your blood flowing correctly.  Strap a treadmill or bike to the wall and your in business.  I wonder if a toilet would work normally in that contraption.  But, oh, if the motor died!<br>
<br>
Just a thought... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/9/02 11:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Scientists explore effects of long-term space travel. </span><hr size=1> The radius of rotation has to be pretty large to minimise gravity gradient and coriolous (I wish I could spell it) forces which could make life difficult.<br>
<br>
Ideally you want to keep the rotation rate below 3 rpm. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/10/02 7:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=44.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Scientists explore effects of long-term space travel. </span><hr size=1> Yes, a big ship would be needed. No problem constructing those in space once we have the industrial infrastructure out there. No problem getting it out there once we have nuclear rockets. Another possibility would be to build a big Orion on Earth. Perhaps in the event of an Armageddon type asteroid coming our way. You could build a Super Orion as big as you like and it would be far more rugged than anything else we might try and build. Which would help with the stress of &quot;Graviton&quot; onboard. It's an interesting idea to put it inside. Ofcourse, the whole ship could be spun but a separate internal system might have it's advantages.<br>
It doesn't seem like a very difficult problem and really it isn't. The reason it is discussed as being problematical by Nasa is that the vehicles they use are horrendously flimsy things that couldn't cope with the stresses on the structure. They can be built for launching stress but exerting centrifugal stresses would make them fly apart. Fanatical weightsaving measures are necessary just to get those big fireworks to LEO. That has it's price. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
