&gt; I fail to see any problems if we go nuclear.<br>
<br>
 I'm split on this.<br>
 On one hand, Mars Direct seems good to me. Let the crew volunteer, based on full knowledge of the risks. Trust them to use their skills to the best, to make it through the mission.<br>
 On the other hand, this does require them to risk only .38 G for more then 2.5 years, and we have no idea what this could do. Making the Mars mission rely on all the R&amp;D to determine this, or else making it wait on further developments of nuclear pulse rockets, instead of using what we have now, means adding billions to the price, and decades to the time before we can start. Maybe best to just do it now, risks &amp; all.<br>
<br>
On the gripping hand, the R&amp;D for NPRs wouldn't necessarily have to be added directly to any one application. If the NPR R&amp;D were re-started, designing an upper stage like the one the original Orion project worked out, then it's applicable to many things. The best might be a first mission going to an NEA with a water factory. This makes the space effort pay back soon, and with huge implications for further space efforts. If a water mine were contributing to a huge profitable space venture, then a Mars mission with 6 weeks one-way travel won't effectively cost a dime, because it's paid for by the space effort.<br>
<br>
 Maybe best of all, would be to make the first mission to Diemos, to plant the water mine at the site further Mars missions are staged from. Then we wouldn't mind a 3 year space flight because most of it is spent in 1G, with full radiation shielding in a stationary &amp; spinning hab. Simplify it by making it _not_ part of a ship, and the most massive parts of the structure come from space resources.<br>
<br>
